question: A 33-year-old man goes to his physician for a routine check of his health status. On physical examination he has the skin lesions seen here. These lesions have not increased in size since childhood. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis? <image 1>
description: The image shows a close-up view of a person's chest area. The skin appears to be covered with a significant amount of hair. There are several small, dark spots scattered across the chest. These spots vary in size but are generally small and round. A ruler is placed at the bottom of the image, indicating that the spots are relatively small, with some measuring less than a centimeter in diameter. The overall appearance suggests benign skin lesions.
